data.content:
Here are better MSTest assertions for each case:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any());              // or CollectionAssert.That.IsNotEmpty if using MSTest 3.x

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive)); // no built-in predicate overload; this one is fine

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3);
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);         // gives "Expected:3 Actual:5" on failure

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null);
    Assert.IsNotNull(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Before | After | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsTrue(x.Any())` | Clearer intent; consider `CollectionAssert` in MSTest v3 |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Failure message shows expected vs actual |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Descriptive failure: *"Assert.IsNotNull failed"* vs generic *"is not true"* |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**
- `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, element)`
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same order
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — any order
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(collection)`

The general rule: prefer the **most specific** assertion — it produces better failure messages and communicates intent more clearly.
